# Chapter 4: System Implementation

## 4.1 Introduction

The Ishara platform is implemented as a distributed three-tier system designed to provide real-time communication with integrated sign language recognition capabilities. This chapter details the architectural design, technological stack, and implementation of the core system components. The system architecture prioritizes low-latency inference, accessibility, and seamless integration between mobile clients, backend services, and machine learning models.

---

## 4.2 System Architecture

### 4.2.1 Three-Tier Architecture Overview

The system follows a distributed three-tier architecture model:

```
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  Tier 1: Flutter Mobile Application Layer            │
│  - User Interface & Interaction                      │
│  - Real-time Video/Audio Streaming                   │
│  - User Authentication & Local Data Management       │
└──────────────────┬───────────────────────────────────┘
                   │ HTTP REST + WebSocket
                   │ (for signaling & control)
┌──────────────────▼───────────────────────────────────┐
│  Tier 2: WebRTC Signaling Server (Node.js)          │
│  - Session Coordination (port 8081)                 │
│  - SDP/ICE Candidate Exchange                       │
│  - Room Management & Participant Tracking           │
│  - STT Bot Initialization                           │
└──────────────────┬───────────────────────────────────┘
                   │ HTTP REST + WebSocket
                   │ (for ML inference & audio)
┌──────────────────▼───────────────────────────────────┐
│  Tier 3: Python/Flask Backend (ML Pipeline)         │
│  - Sign Language Recognition (port 5000)            │
│  - MediaPipe Hand Landmark Extraction               │
│  - TensorFlow/Keras Model Inference                 │
│  - Speech-to-Text Processing (STT Bot)              │
│  - Real-time Feature Engineering                    │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

**Key Design Principles:**

1. **Decoupling:** Each tier operates independently with well-defined interfaces
2. **Scalability:** The signaling and ML tiers can be deployed on separate servers
3. **Real-time Processing:** Direct peer-to-peer media flow minimizes latency for video/audio
4. **Asynchronous Operations:** Non-blocking inference prevents UI freezing
5. **Fault Tolerance:** Comprehensive error handling and fallback mechanisms

### 4.2.2 Communication Protocols

| Component Pair | Protocol | Port | Purpose |
|---|---|---|---|
| Mobile ↔ Signaling Server | WebSocket | 8081 | Session establishment, room management |
| Mobile ↔ Flask API | HTTP REST | 5000 | Sign recognition inference requests |
| Mobile ↔ Remote Peer | WebRTC P2P | Dynamic | Direct encrypted media streaming |
| STT Bot ↔ Signaling Server | WebRTC | Dynamic | Audio capture from conference room |
| STT Bot ↔ Flask API | HTTP + WebSocket | 5005 | Audio processing, result delivery |

---

## 4.3 Frontend Implementation (Flutter)

### 4.3.1 Technological Stack

**Framework & Dependencies:**
- Flutter 3.7.0 with Dart programming language
- State Management: Provider 6.1.1 (reactive ChangeNotifiers)
- Real-time Communication: flutter_webrtc 0.9.35, web_socket_channel 2.4.0
- Authentication: Firebase Auth 5.3.0
- Database: Cloud Firestore 5.4.0, Firebase Storage 12.3.0
- Audio/Speech: speech_to_text 7.3.0 (Google Speech Recognition API)
- Localization: intl 0.19.0 (English/Arabic RTL support)

**Platform Support:**
- Android: Target API 34, minimum API 21
- iOS: Deployment target 11.0 or higher
- Both platforms share 95% of codebase through Flutter's cross-platform architecture

### 4.3.2 Architecture & Code Organization

The Flutter application is organized into five main layers: (presentation, services, models, widgets, utils). Key services include `WebRtcCallService` and `SignLanguageApiService` which manage peer connections and ML API calls respectively.

